WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.160
 - So now we're gonna talk about the actual template language.

00:00:03.160 --> 00:00:05.160
 As I mentioned before, there's more than one

00:00:05.160 --> 00:00:08.020
 templating language, we're using the default one.

00:00:08.020 --> 00:00:10.480
 And I think it's actually one of the better ones,

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:12.920
 this whole notion of double curly braces.

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:16.720
 There's all kind of templating engines,

00:00:16.720 --> 00:00:19.660
 and a lot of 'em use these double curly braces.

00:00:19.660 --> 00:00:21.680
 Sometimes there's a one called mustache,

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:25.040
 because the curly braces look like a mustache.

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:28.140
 So there's double curly braces, you learn it in django,

00:00:28.140 --> 00:00:31.540
 and you'll find it all kinds of other places.

00:00:31.540 --> 00:00:34.040
 I've used it in front-end processing,

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:35.920
 this is back-end processing, 'cause we're doing

00:00:35.920 --> 00:00:37.840
 all the substitution in the back-end.

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:40.440
 So there's basically a couple things you can do,

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:44.520
 the double curly braces, do substitution,

00:00:44.520 --> 00:00:46.440
 and one thing that's cool about this, if you recall,

00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:48.420
 I talked about how you have to escape data

00:00:48.420 --> 00:00:51.360
 that came from the user, anything in the double curly braces

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:53.680
 is automatically escaped, as a matter of fact,

00:00:53.680 --> 00:00:55.440
 you have to do something to not escape it,

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:58.440
 'cause it turns out that 98% of the time,

00:00:58.440 --> 00:01:00.960
 you wanna escape data that you're printing out,

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:02.780
 'cause it doesn't change what it looks like,

00:01:02.780 --> 00:01:04.760
 but it does make sure that it's safe.

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:08.340
 If you add this vertical bar safe afterwards,

00:01:08.340 --> 00:01:11.880
 this vertical bar safe afterwards, that's like a modifier,

00:01:11.880 --> 00:01:13.920
 I think it's called a filter in django,

00:01:13.920 --> 00:01:17.960
 that says look, don't run this, don't run that filter on it

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:21.120
 to do the HTML entities, just do it as is,

00:01:21.120 --> 00:01:22.680
 I know there may be HTML in that,

00:01:22.680 --> 00:01:24.580
 but I've taken care of that because I am

00:01:24.580 --> 00:01:26.600
 the application developer.

00:01:26.600 --> 00:01:30.760
 You can call functions, the code is the curly brace percent,

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:37.320
 and there you tend to call a code, this is like code,

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:40.780
 this is like calling a method or a utility code,

00:01:40.780 --> 00:01:43.240
 and so the first part of this is what you're calling,

00:01:43.240 --> 00:01:45.740
 and then later, you can have some parameters,

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:49.900
 so this URL says, I wanna find a URL for the view cat detail,

00:01:49.900 --> 00:01:54.380
 and I'm gonna take the number that is the current cat

00:01:54.380 --> 00:01:56.520
 as the primary key for the cat record,

00:01:56.520 --> 00:01:59.460
 and put that on as the URL as well.

00:01:59.460 --> 00:02:03.240
 The author in this case is a, and we'll see this later,

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:07.040
 is a model item, and getAbsoluteURL is a method

00:02:07.040 --> 00:02:09.080
 inside that model item.

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:12.120
 You can have sort of ifs and ifs and else's,

00:02:12.120 --> 00:02:14.580
 and it's kind of Python-like, which is nice,

00:02:14.580 --> 00:02:17.620
 in that you don't really have to learn new things.

00:02:17.620 --> 00:02:19.940
 There is looping code that's in there,

00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:22.200
 like a for loop that we'll talk about in a bit,

00:02:22.200 --> 00:02:25.560
 and then there is blocks that can be replaced,

00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:27.860
 so you can have a template that sort of pulls in

00:02:27.860 --> 00:02:30.100
 another template and then substitutes in part of it,

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:32.620
 so you can have whole blocks of substitution,

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:35.040
 not just little strings of substitution,

00:02:35.040 --> 00:02:38.240
 and so we'll talk about each of these in turn.

00:02:38.240 --> 00:02:41.300
 So here we go, we'll start with a real simple one,

00:02:41.300 --> 00:02:45.640
 and you'll notice that in this particular simple one,

00:02:45.640 --> 00:02:48.300
 we have no parameters on the URL,

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:51.160
 so we don't have any parameters here.

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:53.340
 I'm going back to a non-class style,

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:57.180
 just a simple function, and I'm not sending a context.

00:02:57.180 --> 00:03:00.260
 The context would be the third parameter on the render call,

00:03:00.260 --> 00:03:04.180
 and so I'm just saying, hey, and this is what you do

00:03:04.180 --> 00:03:06.680
 when you just have some static HTML

00:03:06.680 --> 00:03:08.200
 that you don't really need to change anything,

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:09.280
 and so that's what's sitting in here,

00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:11.680
 it's just a simple page.

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:14.860
 There's this thing called a built-in template view class

00:03:14.860 --> 00:03:16.820
 that sort of does exactly this thing,

00:03:16.820 --> 00:03:19.380
 that just grabs a template, turns it into an HDB,

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:22.080
 grabs a file, turns it into an HDB response,

00:03:22.080 --> 00:03:23.520
 and sends it back to Django,

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:26.860
 so that's just a super simple template.

00:03:26.860 --> 00:03:31.820
 Now here's one, we're gonna take a parameter to the context,

00:03:31.820 --> 00:03:35.380
 and I'm not taking it from the command line quite yet,

00:03:35.380 --> 00:03:38.300
 I'm just gonna make the parameter always be 42,

00:03:38.300 --> 00:03:42.400
 and the key is, this is a key, and this is a value,

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:46.580
 so zap in this case is the key, and 42 is the value.

00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:48.840
 I often call this variable context,

00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:52.440
 but the fact that's just a mnemonic memory thing for me,

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:55.080
 context or CTX is what I tend to call it,

00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:58.080
 and now I'm passing in the template,

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:03.040
 this template here, the guest.html template,

00:04:03.040 --> 00:04:06.760
 and it has one little curly brace substitution,

00:04:06.760 --> 00:04:11.400
 and remember that does escaping for us automatically,

00:04:11.400 --> 00:04:13.280
 so there's no need to use escape the way there was

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:15.200
 when we were doing this by a concatenation.

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:17.720
 That alone is a good reason to use templates,

00:04:17.720 --> 00:04:20.820
 and so this ends up sending out your guess is 42,

00:04:20.820 --> 00:04:24.480
 so this is just really focusing on what's in that context,

00:04:24.480 --> 00:04:27.320
 and how the things come out of the context.

00:04:27.320 --> 00:04:30.760
 This name here, zap in the context,

00:04:30.760 --> 00:04:32.480
 means pull the thing out of the context

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:36.880
 under the string name zap, and then it substitutes

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:40.040
 the results, like the 42, so instead of it saying

00:04:40.040 --> 00:04:42.420
 guess was zap, it's your guess is 42,

00:04:42.420 --> 00:04:46.920
 so that's really focusing on the substitution.

00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:49.820
 So this is showing us how we do the save stuff

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:53.360
 in case you actually want to pass some HTML into a template

00:04:53.360 --> 00:04:56.040
 and actually want it to render as HTML,

00:04:56.040 --> 00:04:59.460
 not as HTML entities, or HTML entity style.

00:04:59.460 --> 00:05:04.840
 So we're sending in a thing that's bold with a B

00:05:04.840 --> 00:05:06.680
 and a less than B, that's HTML,

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:08.680
 it's got less than's and greater than's in it,

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:13.300
 and then we got zap, and so you can see that

00:05:13.300 --> 00:05:17.140
 zap comes out as 42, it's HTML entities

00:05:17.140 --> 00:05:20.280
 but has no special characters, but if we escape text,

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:23.400
 text is the one with the HTML entity characters,

00:05:23.400 --> 00:05:25.920
 that automatically escapes it so that you see

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:29.800
 the less than's and greater than's in the browser output,

00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:33.040
 escaped, less than B, bold, greater than B, right?

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:36.720
 And if you say text and then add the save filter

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:39.040
 to the end of it, that says don't escape it,

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:42.920
 and so then this bold goes right into the HTML document,

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:45.360
 and instead of you seeing the less than's and greater than's,

00:05:45.360 --> 00:05:47.680
 you're actually seeing the text turn to bold.

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:51.120
 Now usually the bad folks that are trying to get into

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:53.920
 your computer are not just turning your text to bold,

00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:55.200
 they're trying to run JavaScript,

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:56.880
 and all we're showing here is that

00:05:56.880 --> 00:05:59.440
 whatever less than's and greater than's would be

00:05:59.440 --> 00:06:02.760
 in that context value TXT, they're gonna end up

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:04.880
 literally in the document and the browser

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:07.360
 is going to interpret them as HTML.

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:10.440
 I mean there's just no way that somehow your browser knows

00:06:10.440 --> 00:06:13.560
 the HTML that came from your program

00:06:13.560 --> 00:06:16.600
 versus the HTML that came from a context variable,

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:19.080
 because by the time it gets to the browser,

00:06:19.080 --> 00:06:21.280
 it's all one thing, and so it doesn't know,

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:24.300
 oh wow, that's dangerous, that came from a variable.

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:27.680
 Now by the time the response goes back to the browser,

00:06:27.680 --> 00:06:29.480
 it's just a blob of text.

00:06:29.480 --> 00:06:33.060
 Now we can talk about some loops here.

00:06:33.060 --> 00:06:38.640
 I am passing in two arrays,

00:06:38.640 --> 00:06:40.440
 apple, orange, banana, and lychee,

00:06:40.440 --> 00:06:41.800
 and then I'm passing another array

00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:44.160
 called n with peanut and cashew,

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:46.840
 and then I'm going to create a context,

00:06:46.840 --> 00:06:49.080
 and in that context I'm gonna have fruits

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:53.880
 point at the list f, nuts point at the list n,

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:56.760
 and then zap is just the string 42,

00:06:56.760 --> 00:07:00.040
 and do I even use zap in this one?

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:02.680
 No, I think there's another place that it,

00:07:02.680 --> 00:07:05.300
 no, oh yeah, yeah, I just don't have it in the,

00:07:07.240 --> 00:07:10.000
 so here's the template, a part of the template,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.520
 it's not looking at zap, and so here's the key,

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:16.280
 so we got this for loop, four x in fruits,

00:07:16.280 --> 00:07:19.280
 well fruits is looking up something in the context

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:23.280
 under the key fruits, they don't look like strings in,

00:07:23.280 --> 00:07:27.740
 they don't look like strings in the template,

00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:31.920
 but it looks up there and it finds a list,

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:35.280
 so that little list f is what really is going on here,

00:07:35.280 --> 00:07:38.720
 and f is a list of apple, orange, banana, lychee,

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:41.120
 and then x becomes the iteration variable,

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:43.660
 that's only within the template,

00:07:43.660 --> 00:07:45.520
 and then I'm gonna print it out,

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:46.360
 and then I'm gonna end it,

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:49.440
 so that's like the start and end of a for loop,

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:50.880
 apple, orange, banana, lychee.

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:53.400
 Now, you'll notice that I have an li tag,

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:55.120
 which is the list item tag,

00:07:55.120 --> 00:07:57.640
 and it just generates all that HTML,

00:07:57.640 --> 00:08:00.900
 and again, the double curly braces

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:03.740
 are doing HTML entity escaping automatically.

00:08:05.080 --> 00:08:09.160
 So, we take a look at nuts,

00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:11.400
 so we ask is nuts present,

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:16.400
 'cause that's a way to tell if variables present or absent,

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:20.160
 if it's absent, I'm going to ask another filter on the end

00:08:20.160 --> 00:08:22.320
 saying how long was it, okay,

00:08:22.320 --> 00:08:25.160
 and so this is just, this is the n,

00:08:25.160 --> 00:08:30.120
 nuts is the n list, and it has a length of two,

00:08:30.120 --> 00:08:31.680
 which means it has two elements in it,

00:08:31.680 --> 00:08:33.600
 and so we see the number two,

00:08:33.600 --> 00:08:35.200
 and so you can do various things,

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:37.200
 so this is, and this is an if then else,

00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:39.380
 the syntax of an if then else,

00:08:39.380 --> 00:08:42.360
 with curly brace, curly brace percent.

00:08:42.360 --> 00:08:47.840
 Now, we can pass objects within objects,

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:50.180
 and so, it's a little tricky,

00:08:50.180 --> 00:08:53.340
 we have a context in this x variable,

00:08:53.340 --> 00:08:58.320
 and the, sort of the outer key is pointing,

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:02.000
 the key is, outer is pointing to another dictionary,

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.240
 and in that dictionary, there is a key of inner

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:09.720
 with a value of 42, and then we render the nested.html,

00:09:09.720 --> 00:09:11.820
 and you see the outer,

00:09:11.820 --> 00:09:15.280
 but then outer.inner, that's,

00:09:15.280 --> 00:09:20.120
 so outer is that object, and then object.inner,

00:09:20.120 --> 00:09:23.280
 then this thing becomes 42, okay,

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:25.440
 so you can kind of walk through objects

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:29.420
 if you have hierarchical objects,

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:32.400
 objects that are, objects that contain objects,

00:09:32.400 --> 00:09:33.760
 or lists that contain objects,

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:35.840
 or any number of hierarchical structure

00:09:35.840 --> 00:09:39.920
 of lists and objects, you can walk through them.

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:44.120
 So here's just another simple example,

00:09:44.120 --> 00:09:47.600
 this one has data coming in instead of hard coded,

00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:50.760
 so we again have, you know, game 200,

00:09:50.760 --> 00:09:53.280
 and we're running into game view,

00:09:53.280 --> 00:09:57.520
 it's a class view, and the 200 comes in as the parameter,

00:09:57.520 --> 00:09:58.880
 because we said it's the parameter

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:00.680
 that comes after the word game,

00:10:00.680 --> 00:10:03.000
 and so guess comes in as 200,

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:04.200
 it's a string at this point,

00:10:04.200 --> 00:10:06.080
 it hasn't been converted to an integer,

00:10:06.080 --> 00:10:08.640
 so when Django pulls these off,

00:10:08.640 --> 00:10:11.320
 well, it does some validation based on the types,

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:14.720
 but it doesn't actually necessarily convert them,

00:10:14.720 --> 00:10:16.420
 and so we're going to create a context,

00:10:16.420 --> 00:10:19.200
 x equals, you know, a key of guess,

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:22.240
 and convert it to an integer to pass it in,

00:10:22.240 --> 00:10:24.480
 and then we're gonna pass the context in

00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:27.560
 and the template in, and so the word guess

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:30.060
 is gonna come out, and we sort of saw this,

00:10:30.060 --> 00:10:33.020
 the guess is 200, and then depending on the if then else

00:10:33.020 --> 00:10:35.580
 logic, it's gonna say, in this case,

00:10:35.580 --> 00:10:37.620
 too high, because your guess was 200,

00:10:37.620 --> 00:10:41.540
 and of course the right answer is always 42.

00:10:41.540 --> 00:10:43.720
 So now we're gonna talk a little bit about

00:10:43.720 --> 00:10:47.400
 how you manage a common text going from one template

00:10:47.400 --> 00:10:50.580
 to another through template inheritance.

00:10:57.560 --> 00:10:59.320
 (jazz music)

